\section{Problem 1}
\label{sec:org694cbcc}

\subsection{a}
\label{sec:orgd8f8c77}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./problem1_first.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Like the problem asked I solved this using a second order finite difference and first order Neumann boundary condition scheme
\item The slope is about \textasciitilde{}1 in loglog space which means the error goes with \(\Delta\) x
\end{itemize}
\subsection{b}
\label{sec:org36785e9}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./problem1_second.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item Like the problem asked I solved this using a second order finite difference and second order Neumann boundary condition scheme
\item This boundary condition does a far better job than the first one
\item The slope is about \textasciitilde{}4 in loglog space which means the error goes with (\(\Delta\) x)\textsuperscript{4}
\end{itemize}
\subsection{c}
\label{sec:orgbb65baa}
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=.9\linewidth]{./problem1_richardson.png}
\end{center}
\begin{itemize}
\item The richardson extrapolation does far better than the normal numerical solution
\item The convergence rate isn't appreciably larger than part b it looks like it is also around a slope of 4.
\item I really don't get why that is when the absolute error is so clearly way smaller.
\end{itemize}

